				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\hbox {LH}_2$$\end{document} provides the best combination of efficiency, flexibility, and investment cost over the majority of scenarios. In particular, temporally flexible large-scale supply chains make use of renewable surplus generation, which allows reducing optimal renewable capacity investment. Yet this flexibility not only facilitates renewable integration in the power sector, but can also increase the use of conventional generation with low marginal costs, with respective carbon emission effects (cp.29). The emission intensity of hydrogen thus not necessarily decreases with higher renewable shares, absent further CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
